In a subsequent study, the selectivity performance of the sC-dots-DNA was evaluated by assessing the fluorescence response to the ions including Pb2+, Mn2+, Ni2+, Cu2+, Bi3+ and Ag+. As displayed in Fig. 4E, Hg2+ can significantly quench the fluorescence intensity of sC-dots-DNA, while the other ions do not behave the same quenching effect, indicating that Hg2+ are specific recognized by sC-dot-DNA. To intuitively show the improvement of selectivity performance of Hg2+ by C-dots, here, we have introduced the selectivity coefficient (K) concept to express the difference before and after the surface change of C-dots quantitatively. The selectivity coefficient (K) is defined as the ratio of the concentration of Hg2+ to the interfering ions, when producing the same fluorescence quenching effect. The smaller of the value is, the better of the selectivity performance will be. The result of the selectivity coefficient of C-dots and sC-dots-DNA is displayed in Table 1
                     . It is obviously that the value of all selectivity coefficients showed several orders of magnitude decrease after the surface change of C-dots, indicating an enhanced selectivity performance of sC-dots-DNA towards Hg2+. Based on the surface chemistry strategy, our C-dots can not only achieve the detection sensitivity and detection limit equivalent to those in the Hg2+ sensing literatures (as displayed in Table 2
                     ) without any signal amplification steps, but also can effectively improve the selectivity performance of Hg2+.
